              <span id="reviewTextContainer37363944" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5474399863917561699">This book is a comprehensive study of the history of chocolate. The authors are academics and the book reads as such. It can be a bit dry, but if you are keen, there is much to learn about the cultural and political importance of chocolate from the Aztecs and Mayans to the elite of Boroque Europe, the slave trade and the spread of the drink around the globe to the post-industrial revolution inventions by Nestle, Cadbury, Hershey, etc. ..even Green &amp; Blacks. If you are a chocoholic or a history b</span>
  <span id="freeText5474399863917561699" style="display:none">This book is a comprehensive study of the history of chocolate. The authors are academics and the book reads as such. It can be a bit dry, but if you are keen, there is much to learn about the cultural and political importance of chocolate from the Aztecs and Mayans to the elite of Boroque Europe, the slave trade and the spread of the drink around the globe to the post-industrial revolution inventions by Nestle, Cadbury, Hershey, etc. ..even Green &amp; Blacks. If you are a chocoholic or a history buff than take a read. I enjoyed it and it certainly made me want to try the early meso-american version of the chocolate drink that was roasted and ground cocoa beans mixed with water and "flavorings" , spices mostly, but also maize and later bread, then mixed to make a frothy head. Sounds Yum! </span>
