<div id="review_914455933" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/914455933" />
    <a title="Denise Louise" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12481458-denise-louise"><img alt="Denise Louise" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1346682018p2/12481458.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/914455933?book_show_action=true">Apr 19, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Denise Louise" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Denise Louise" href="/user/show/12481458-denise-louise">Denise Louise</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer914455933" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2251228628604482513">It&apos;s a pity this book had such a stilted and old-fashioned style, because it could have been a very good book otherwise. Probably two thirds of the book is detailed, scholarly history of chocolate in Pre-Columbian Mesoamerica and its slow introduction into Europe after discovery (that is, conquest) of the New World. The story of development of chocolate from drink to food was not nearly so richly explained, and the end of the book feels quite rushed. Unfortunately, the book&apos;s tone in straight fr</span>
  <span id="freeText2251228628604482513" style="display:none">It's a pity this book had such a stilted and old-fashioned style, because it could have been a very good book otherwise. Probably two thirds of the book is detailed, scholarly history of chocolate in Pre-Columbian Mesoamerica and its slow introduction into Europe after discovery (that is, conquest) of the New World. The story of development of chocolate from drink to food was not nearly so richly explained, and the end of the book feels quite rushed. Unfortunately, the book's tone in straight from the 1950s (or earlier) even though its copyright is late 1990s, so it was difficult to enjoy. Let's just say.......the reader should note that, although one must admit the book in question accurately portrays the depth of its subject, we must conclude that there are other tomes that would be equally informative, and the reader is thusly advised to pursue them.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2251228628604482513" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


