<div id="review_29183829" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/29183829" />
    <a title="Pancha" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/634200-pancha"><img alt="Pancha" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1195692792p2/634200.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/29183829?book_show_action=true">Aug 03, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Pancha" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Pancha" href="/user/show/634200-pancha">Pancha</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/634200-pancha?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/634200-pancha?shelf=food">food</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer29183829" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer926577552408028976">Some of the Maya and Aztec info is in her earlier book on Mesoamerican cuisine, but there is enough extra material that I didn&apos;t feel like I was just rereading something previously published. The first third of the book focuses on the history of chocolate in America, up to the Conquest. Then the focus shifts to Europe and how chocolate was introduced there. Finally, the last chapter focuses on modern chocolate manufacture as well as the recent rise in gourmet chocolate. The Coes include a quick </span>
  <span id="freeText926577552408028976" style="display:none">Some of the Maya and Aztec info is in her earlier book on Mesoamerican cuisine, but there is enough extra material that I didn't feel like I was just rereading something previously published. The first third of the book focuses on the history of chocolate in America, up to the Conquest. Then the focus shifts to Europe and how chocolate was introduced there. Finally, the last chapter focuses on modern chocolate manufacture as well as the recent rise in gourmet chocolate. The Coes include a quick but comprehensive breakdown of possible origins of the word chocolate. It is most likely a combination of the Maya verb <i>chokola'j</i> (to drink chocolate together) and the Aztec word <i>atl</i> (water) which was bastardized by Spanish pronunciation to <i>ate</i>. </span>
  <a data-text-id="926577552408028976" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


